    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Inequalities allow us to compare quantities using symbols like <m>\gt</m> (greater than), <m>\lt</m> (less than), <m>\ge</m> (greater than or equal to), and <m>\le</m> (less than or equal to). Solving a simple linear inequality in one unknown follows the exact same steps as solving a standard equation, such as grouping like terms.
        </p>
        <p>
            However, there is one critical rule you must always remember: Whenever you multiply or divide both sides of an inequality by a negative number,the inequality sign must reverse (flip) its direction.
        </p>
        <p>
            For instance, if <m>-x \lt 5</m>, dividing by <m>-1</m> results in <m>x \gt -5</m>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the inequality <m>15 - 2x \ge 7</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First you subtract <m>15</m> from both sides to group the constants:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \ge 7 - 15</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \ge -8 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then we divide both sides by <m>-2</m>. Since we are dividing by a negative number, we must flip the inequality symbol from <m>\ge</m> to <m>\le</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp \le \frac{-8}{-2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp \le 4</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the following inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>3x - 9 \lt 6 + x</me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, we group the variable terms on one side and the constants on the other side. We can do this by subtracting <m>x</m> from both sides and adding <m>9</m> to both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>3x - x \amp \lt 6 + 9</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \lt 15</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then we divide both sides by <m>2</m> to solve for <m>x</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp \lt \frac{15}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp \lt 7.5</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Shireri</em> primary school has a handwashing water tank that currently holds <m>80</m> litres of water. The tap has a slight leak and loses water at a rate of <m>4</m> litres every hour. The school security guard wants to ensure there are always strictly more than <m>20</m> litres left in the tank for the afternoon classes.
            </p>
            <p>
                If <m>h</m> represents the number of hours the tank has been leaking, write an inequality for this situation and solve for <m>h</m> to find out how many hours the water will remain above the <m>20</m>-litre mark.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We can start by writing an expression for the amount of water left in the tank after <m>h</m> hours. Since the tank loses <m>4</m> litres every hour, the amount of water lost after <m>h</m> hours is <m>4h</m>. Therefore, the amount of water left in the tank after <m>h</m> hours can be expressed as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Water left} \amp = 80 - 4h </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The security guard wants to ensure that there are always more than <m>20</m> litres left, so we can set up the inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 80 - 4h \amp \gt 20</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, we solve for <m>h</m>. First, we subtract <m>80</m> from both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>-4h \amp \gt 20 - 80 </mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                    <mrow>-4h \amp \gt -60</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then we divide both sides by <m>-4</m>. Since we are dividing by a negative number, we must flip the inequality symbol from <m>\gt</m> to <m>\lt</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>h \amp \lt \frac{-60}{-4}</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                    <mrow>h \amp \lt 15</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the water will remain above the <m>20</m>-litre mark for less than <m>15</m> hours.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

